Space Complexity: O(n), due to the memoization array dp storing
                        results for all indices from 0 to n-1.











                    Tabulation Approach






                            Algorithm




                            In this variation of the classic frog jump problem, the frog can jump from any stone to one
                            of the previous k stones. The cost of each jump is the absolute difference in
                            height between the stones. The goal is to minimize the total cost to reach the last stone
                            starting from the first.


                            Instead of using recursion with memoization, we can solve this iteratively using bottom-up
                            dynamic programming. This helps avoid recursion stack overhead and provides an efficient way
                            to build the solution from the base case.


                            We use a dp[] array where dp[i] represents the minimum cost to
                            reach the ith stone.

We initialize dp[0] = 0 because the frog starts there with no cost.
For every stone from index 1 to n-1, we try all possible jump
                                lengths j from 1 to k.
For every valid jump, we compute the cost as
                                dp[i - j] + abs(height[i] - height[i - j]).

We take the minimum of all such possible jump costs and store it in dp[i].

Finally, dp[n - 1] contains the minimum cost to reach the last stone.






